{"paperId": "4568b534a022dd871e9b5a29bb872af83254a741", "abstract": "We propose a multi-layer variational autoencoder method, we call HR-VQVAE, that learns hierarchical discrete representations of the data. By utilizing a novel objective function, each layer in HR-VQVAE learns a discrete representation of the residual from previous layers through a vector quantized encoder. Furthermore, the representations at each layer are hierarchically linked to those at previous layers. We evaluate our method on the tasks of image reconstruction and generation. Experimental results demonstrate that the discrete representations learned by HR-VQVAE enable the decoder to reconstruct high-quality images with less distortion than the baseline methods, namely VQVAE and VQVAE-2. HR-VQVAE can also generate high-quality and diverse images that outperform state-of-the-art generative models, providing further verification of the efficiency of the learned representations. The hierarchical nature of HR-VQVAE i) reduces the decoding search time, making the method particularly suitable for high-load tasks and ii) allows to increase the codebook size without incurring the codebook collapse problem.", "venue": "British Machine Vision Conference", "year": 2022, "citationCount": 2, "influentialCitationCount": 0, "openAccessPdf": {"url": "http://arxiv.org/pdf/2208.04554", "status": "GREEN"}, "tldr": {"model": "tldr@v2.0.0", "text": "The hierarchical nature of HR-VQVAE reduces the decoding search time, making the method particularly suitable for high-load tasks and allows to increase the codebooks size without incurring the codebook collapse problem."}, "embedding": {"model": "specter_v2", "vector": [0.1755790412425995, 0.43759071826934814, 0.2059461623430252, 0.5315006375312805, -0.39759954810142517, 0.1380263715982437, 0.40295082330703735, -0.6261823773384094, -0.08048538118600845, -0.488818883895874, 0.5911777019500732, 0.41083282232284546, 0.32859325408935547, -0.375384658575058, -0.458715438842